                    <div class="position-absolute w-100 text-center" style="bottom:-5px;left:0;">
                        <span data-rcp-follow-member="Torrey"></span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="text-left" style="line-height: 1.2;">

<!--                    <div>-->
<!--                        --><!--                    </div>-->
                    <div>
                        <a href="https://www.justapinch.com/me/torrey" rel="nofollow" data-recipe-username>
                            Torrey Moseley                        </a>
                    </div>
                    <div class="small text-muted">Dallas, TX</div>
                    <div class="small text-muted">
                                                    Updated on Oct 28, 2025                                            </div>
                </div>

            </div>
                                                        <div class="Xrcp-read-more-mobile mb-3" id="recipe-notess">
            <p class="rcp-ugc-block">I ran across this recipe a few years back from my local grocery store. I was very skeptical that one could cook an entire turkey (regardless of size) in about 2 hours and have it edible. Well, not only does this actually work, it produces the BEST roasted turkey I've had to date. No more getting up at 4 a.m. to start the holiday turkey, NO MORE BASTING. It's so incredibly fast and easy. It has become the only way I roast turkeys. Turkey...it's not JUST for holidays, anymore. The biggest turkey I made this way was 22.5 pounds. It took about 2 hours 15 minutes to cook. WOW.</p>
                    </div>
                            </div>
                </div>
            </div>



